<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xml:lang="en"><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="4.3.4">Jekyll</generator><link href="https://jcksanderson.github.io/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="https://jcksanderson.github.io/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" hreflang="en"/><updated>2024-12-16T21:27:31+00:00</updated><id>https://jcksanderson.github.io/feed.xml</id><title type="html">blank</title><subtitle>Jack Sanderson&apos;s Website </subtitle><entry><title type="html">Test Blog Post</title><link href="https://jcksanderson.github.io/blog/2024/distill/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Test Blog Post"/><published>2024-12-15T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2024-12-15T00:00:00+00:00</updated><id>https://jcksanderson.github.io/blog/2024/distill</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://jcksanderson.github.io/blog/2024/distill/"><![CDATA[<h2 id="equations">Equations</h2> <h3 id="subsection-1">Subsection 1</h3> <p>We can write inline equations. For example, Wilson’s theorem states that for any prime \(p\), \((p - 1)! \cong_p -1\).</p> <h3 id="subsection-2">Subsection 2</h3> <p>Alternatively, we can have centered equations:</p> \[a^{p - 1} \cong_p 1\] <hr/> <h2 id="footnotes">Footnotes</h2> <p>This text has a footnote.<d-footnote>Wow!</d-footnote></p> <hr/> <h2 id="code-blocks">Code Blocks</h2> <p>This is probably ugly:</p> <d-code block="" language="C"> int x = 15; int increment(int x) { x++; return x; } </d-code> <p>This way uses the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">highlight</code> liquid tag:</p> <figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-c" data-lang="c"><span class="kt">int</span> <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">;</span>
<span class="kt">int</span> <span class="nf">increment</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="kt">int</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>
  <span class="n">x</span><span class="o">++</span><span class="p">;</span>
  <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">;</span>
<span class="p">}</span></code></pre></figure> <hr/> <h2 id="other-typography">Other Typography?</h2> <p>This is simple back tick code:</p> <div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="sh">"</span><span class="s">Python syntax highlighting</span><span class="sh">"</span>
<span class="k">print</span> <span class="n">s</span>
</code></pre></div></div> <p>And we can have markdown tables:</p> <table> <thead> <tr> <th>Markdown</th> <th>Less</th> <th>Pretty</th> </tr> </thead> <tbody> <tr> <td><em>Still</em></td> <td><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">renders</code></td> <td><strong>nicely</strong></td> </tr> <tr> <td>1</td> <td>2</td> <td>3</td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <blockquote> <p>As well as blockquotes! They can go over multiple lines.</p> </blockquote>]]></content><author><name>Jack Sanderson</name></author><category term="distill"/><category term="formatting"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Messing around with math and code formatting.]]></summary></entry></feed>